## Example 2 — Apply Common Logarithms to Real-World Problems

### Step 1: Solve the Bacteria Growth Problem

The number of bacteria after [t] hours is [N = 1000(2)^t]. We need [t] when [N = 50,000].

[50000 = 1000(2)^t]
[50 = 2^t]
[\log 50 = \log 2^t]
[\log 50 = t \cdot \log 2]
[t = \frac{\log 50}{\log 2} \approx \frac{1.6990}{0.3010} \approx 5.64] hours

### Step 2: Solve the Sound Intensity Problem

Loudness is [L = 10 \log R]. If the siren is 138 decibels, find how many times greater than the threshold.

[138 = 10 \log R]
[13.8 = \log R]
[R = 10^{13.8} \approx 6.31 \times 10^{13}]

The siren is approximately [6.31 \times 10^{13}] times the minimum threshold.

## Example 3 — Solve Exponential Equations

Solve each equation. Round to the nearest ten-thousandth.

### Step 1: Apply the Logarithm Method

[4^{5k} = 37]
[\log 4^{5k} = \log 37]
[5k \cdot \log 4 = \log 37]
[k = \frac{\log 37}{5 \cdot \log 4} \approx \frac{1.5682}{5(0.6021)} \approx \frac{1.5682}{3.0105} \approx 0.5209]

[8^p = 50]
[p \cdot \log 8 = \log 50]
[p = \frac{\log 50}{\log 8} \approx \frac{1.6990}{0.9031} \approx 1.8813]

[7^y = 15]
[y \cdot \log 7 = \log 15]
[y = \frac{\log 15}{\log 7} \approx \frac{1.1761}{0.8451} \approx 1.3915]

### Step 2: Solve More Complex Equations

[5^{4x - 2} = 120]
[(4x - 2) \cdot \log 5 = \log 120]
[4x - 2 = \frac{\log 120}{\log 5} \approx \frac{2.0792}{0.6990} \approx 2.9747]
[4x = 4.9747]
[x \approx 1.2437]

[6^{x + 2} = 18]
[(x + 2) \cdot \log 6 = \log 18]
[x + 2 = \frac{\log 18}{\log 6} \approx \frac{1.2553}{0.7782} \approx 1.6133]
[x \approx -0.3867]

[2.4^{x + 4} = 30]
[(x + 4) \cdot \log 2.4 = \log 30]
[x + 4 = \frac{\log 30}{\log 2.4} \approx \frac{1.4771}{0.3802} \approx 3.8851]
[x \approx -0.1149]

## Example 4 — Solve Logarithmic Inequalities

Solve each inequality. Round to the nearest ten-thousandth.

### Step 1: Use Logarithms to Isolate the Variable

[7^{3x - 1} \geq 21]
[(3x - 1) \cdot \log 7 \geq \log 21]
[3x - 1 \geq \frac{\log 21}{\log 7} \approx \frac{1.3222}{0.8451} \approx 1.5647]
[3x \geq 2.5647]
[x \geq 0.8549]

[6.5^{2x} \geq 200]
[2x \cdot \log 6.5 \geq \log 200]
[2x \geq \frac{\log 200}{\log 6.5} \approx \frac{2.3010}{0.8129} \approx 2.8301]
[x \geq 1.4151]

### Step 2: Handle Special Cases

[3^x > 243]
Since [243 = 3^5], we have [3^x > 3^5]. Since base 3 > 1, [x > 5].

[16^v \leq \frac{1}{4}]
Since [\frac{1}{4} = 16^{-1/2}], we have [16^v \leq 16^{-1/2}]. Since base 16 > 1, [v \leq -\frac{1}{2}].

[8^{y + 4} > 15]
[(y + 4) \cdot \log 8 > \log 15]
[y + 4 > \frac{\log 15}{\log 8} \approx \frac{1.1761}{0.9031} \approx 1.3023]
[y > -2.6977]

[2^x < 25]
Since [25 = 5^2 = 2^{\log_2 25}], we need [\log_2 25]. Alternatively, [x \cdot \log 2 < \log 25], so [x < \frac{\log 25}{\log 2} \approx \frac{1.3979}{0.3010} \approx 4.6439].

## Example 5 — Express Logarithms in Terms of Common Logarithms

Use the Change of Base Formula to express each logarithm in terms of common logs, then approximate.

### Step 1: Apply Change of Base Formula

[\log_4 22 = \frac{\log 22}{\log 4} \approx \frac{1.3424}{0.6021} \approx 2.2293]

[\log_{12} 200 = \frac{\log 200}{\log 12} \approx \frac{2.3010}{1.0792} \approx 2.1316]

[\log_2 50 = \frac{\log 50}{\log 2} \approx \frac{1.6990}{0.3010} \approx 5.6439]

[\log_8 15 = \frac{\log 15}{\log 8} \approx \frac{1.1761}{0.9031} \approx 1.3023]

[\log_3 2 = \frac{\log 2}{\log 3} \approx \frac{0.3010}{0.4771} \approx 0.6309]

[\log_5 0.4 = \frac{\log 0.4}{\log 5} \approx \frac{-0.3979}{0.6990} \approx -0.5693]

## Example 6 — Use Estimation in Real-World Models

### Step 1: Solve the Restaurant Revenue Problem

Revenue is [r = 180 + 35 \log_4 x], where [r] is in thousands and [x] is advertising in thousands. Find [x] when [r = 250] (thousands).

[250 = 180 + 35 \log_4 x]
[70 = 35 \log_4 x]
[2 = \log_4 x]
[x = 4^2 = 16]

So $16,000 spent on advertising yields $250,000 revenue.

### Step 2: Solve the Deer Population Problem

The function [f(x) = 2 + 10 \log_9 (x + 2)] gives deer population in hundreds, where [x] is years since 2012. Find when [f(x) = 15] (1500 deer).

[15 = 2 + 10 \log_9 (x + 2)]
[13 = 10 \log_9 (x + 2)]
[1.3 = \log_9 (x + 2)]
[x + 2 = 9^{1.3}]
[x = 9^{1.3} - 2]

Using calculator: [9^{1.3} \approx 20.29], so [x \approx 18.29]. The year is approximately [2012 + 18 = 2030].

